{card:transitionfunctions}
{widgets}
button1:{"type":"button","size":[60,20],"pos":[442,312],"script":"whatisatransition.0","text":"Next","style":"rect"}
button2:{"type":"button","size":[60,20],"pos":[10,312],"script":"whatisatransition.0","text":"Prev","style":"rect"}
title:{"type":"field","size":[492,17],"pos":[10,22],"locked":1,"font":"menu","show":"invert","border":1,"align":"center","value":"Transition Functions"}
button3:{"type":"button","size":[60,20],"pos":[78,312],"script":"whatisatransition.0","text":"Index","style":"rect"}
field1:{"type":"field","size":[240,259],"pos":[262,47],"locked":1,"border":0,"value":{"text":["The heart of a transition is a function which takes four arguments:\n\n- A ","canvas"," widget the size of the screen.\n\n- An ","image"," of the source card.\n\n- An ","image"," of the destination card.\n\n- A ","number"," between 0 and 1 giving a \"tweening\" value for the animation.\n\nUsing the images and the tweening value, the function should draw something on the canvas.\n\nUsually, when the tweening value is 0 the function should draw the source image, when the tweening value is 1 it should draw the destination image, and for any value in-between the function should draw some combination of the images.\n\nWith an appropriately written function, an enormous range of transitions are possible. We'll explore some ideas on the following cards."],"font":["","menu","","menu","","menu","","menu",""],"arg":["","","","","","","","",""]}}
ex1:{"type":"field","size":[240,101],"pos":[10,71],"style":"code","value":"on BoxIn c a b t do\n c.rect[(c.size/2) (c.size*t) \"center\"]\n c.merge[a b]\nend"}

{card:transitionregistration}
{widgets}
button1:{"type":"button","size":[60,20],"pos":[442,312],"script":"whatisatransition.0","text":"Next","style":"rect"}
button2:{"type":"button","size":[60,20],"pos":[10,312],"script":"whatisatransition.0","text":"Prev","style":"rect"}
title:{"type":"field","size":[492,17],"pos":[10,22],"locked":1,"font":"menu","show":"invert","border":1,"align":"center","value":"Transition Installation"}
button3:{"type":"button","size":[60,20],"pos":[78,312],"script":"whatisatransition.0","text":"Index","style":"rect"}
field1:{"type":"field","size":[240,258],"pos":[262,48],"locked":1,"border":0,"value":"To define new transitions, you'll need to declare them to Decker with the transition[] function.\n\nCalling transition[] with a function will register a transition of the same name, allowing it to appear in the \"Action...\" dialog and be used by go[] in the future. If a module uses transition[], deckbuilders will not need to do any scripting to take advantage of the new transitions!\n\n\n\n\nCalling transition[] will also return a dictionary of the currently registered transitions, allowing you to easily enumerate their names or retrieve a transition's function for use elsewhere, as in many of this deck's interactive demonstrations."}
ex1:{"type":"field","size":[240,82],"pos":[10,51],"style":"code","value":"transition[\n on MyTransition c a b t do\n  \n  # draw something...\n  \n end\n]"}
names:{"type":"field","size":[224,70],"pos":[21,161],"volatile":1,"scrollbar":1,"style":"code"}
ex2:{"type":"field","size":[240,21],"pos":[11,238],"style":"code","value":"names.data:keys transition[]"}
demobtn:{"type":"button","size":[79,29],"pos":[94,263],"script":"transitionregistration.0","show":"invert","text":"Try It!","style":"rect"}

{script:transitionregistration.0}
on click do
 eval[ex2.text () 1]
end
{end}

{card:canvasdrawing}
script:"canvasdrawing.0"
{widgets}
button1:{"type":"button","size":[60,20],"pos":[442,312],"script":"whatisatransition.0","text":"Next","style":"rect"}
button2:{"type":"button","size":[60,20],"pos":[10,312],"script":"whatisatransition.0","text":"Prev","style":"rect"}
title:{"type":"field","size":[492,17],"pos":[10,22],"locked":1,"font":"menu","show":"invert","border":1,"align":"center","value":"Background: Canvas Drawing"}
button3:{"type":"button","size":[60,20],"pos":[78,312],"script":"whatisatransition.0","text":"Index","style":"rect"}
field1:{"type":"field","size":[245,259],"pos":[257,47],"locked":1,"border":0,"value":{"text":["Before we dive into writing our own transitions, let's briefly explore a few supporting concepts: canvas drawing, compositing images with canvas.merge[], and tweening.\n","\nCanvas widgets"," offer a wide range of functions for drawing  programmatically, including:\n\n","canvas.clear[]"," for erasing the canvas.\n\n","canvas.rect[pos size]"," for filled rectangles.\n\n","canvas.poly[points]"," for filled polygons.\n\n","canvas.paste[image pos]"," for drawing an image on the canvas. The second argument can specify a size to squash or stretch the image into, and a third argument, if truthy, can ask for the image to be drawn with transparency.\n\nAll sizes and positions are in pixels, relative to the top left corner of the canvas."],"font":["","","","menu","","menu","","menu","","menu",""],"arg":["","http://beyondloom.com/decker/decker.html#canvasinterface","","","","","","","","",""]}}
ex1:{"type":"field","size":[240,129],"pos":[10,47],"script":"canvasdrawing.1","scrollbar":1,"style":"code","value":"c.clear[]\n\nc.rect[(10,40) (30,50)]\n\nc.poly[(100,20) (110,40) (80,50)]\n\ni:image[\"%%IMG0AAcAB0Bg0Ij8goA=\"]\nc.paste[i (130,70)]\nc.paste[i (130,30,20,20)]"}
c:{"type":"canvas","size":[167,100],"pos":[54,191],"locked":1,"volatile":1,"scale":1}

{script:canvasdrawing.0}
on view do
 eval[ex1.text () 1]
end
{end}

